# Vendored from https://github.com/eyereasoner/eye/blob/master/reasoning/good-cobbler/
# (cobbler.n3 facts + cobbler-query.n3 rule combined). Unmodified besides
# combining the two upstream files and adding a second, decomposing rule
# (see below).
#
# Previously blocked on list-pattern structural unification (see
# manifest.json's history and triples.rs's `unify_list_pattern`/
# `is_nonground_list_pattern`, now implemented) -- closed by
# `TripleIndex::query`'s new `query_list_pattern` fallback, which unifies
# a variable-containing list pattern like `(:good ?Y)` against a
# separately-parsed ground list `(:good :Cobbler)` member-by-member.
@prefix : <https://eyereasoner.github.io/ns#>.
@prefix list: <http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/list#>.

:joe :is (:good :Cobbler).

{
    ?X :is (:good ?Y).
} => {
    ?X :is (:good ?Y).
}.

# A second rule decomposing the list-unification result into a scalar fact
# -- the original list-to-list rule above IS the real EYE test, but its
# derived fact (`?X :is (fresh list)`) isn't directly comparable via this
# suite's simple textual fact-set check (each parse assigns a fresh,
# non-comparable opaque list-term id -- see filter.n3's identical note).
# This rule's output (`?X :hasGoodTrait ?Y`) is a plain scalar triple, so
# it's what the vendored `_result.n3` actually checks.
{
    ?X :is (:good ?Y).
} => {
    ?X :hasGoodTrait ?Y.
}.
